				\begin{document}$${n}_{p}^{2}$$\end{document}) (0.01, 0.06, and 0.14 indicating small, medium, and large effects, respectively [42]), from the repeated measures ANOVA. Standardized differences were also calculated for pairwise comparisons using Hedges’ g ES with 95% confidence intervals (CI), as recommended by Lakens [43]. Hedges’ g is bias-corrected and particularly appropriate when a sample size is < 20 [43]. This statistic enables quantification of the practical magnitude of differences between conditions in a scale-independent manner, facilitates meta-analytic comparisons across studies, and informs a priori power analyses for future research [43, 44]. Hedges’ g ES was deemed unclear if the 95% CI overlapped both substantially positive (0.20) and negative (-0.20) values [45].

